## 2. Velocity, Speed, Acceleration — Kinematics of Curves

When a curve **r(t)** describes a particle's position, its derivative **v(t) = r'(t)** is the **velocity** (a vector), and the magnitude **||v(t)||** is the **speed**. The second derivative **a(t) = r''(t)** is the **acceleration**.

### Example 2.1: Velocity and Speed of a Projectile

A projectile **r(t) = (v₀ cos θ · t, v₀ sin θ · t - ½ g t²)**.

```scheme
(define (projectile-kinematics)
  (let* ((v0 20)
         (theta (/ (const/pi) 4))
         (g 9.8)
         (r (lambda (t)
              (list (* v0 (geom/cos theta) t)
                    (- (* v0 (geom/sin theta) t)
                       (* 0.5 g t t)))))
         (v (curve/velocity r))
         (speed (curve/speed r))
         (a (curve/accel r)))
    (list 'at-t=1
          (list 'position (r 1))
          (list 'velocity (v 1))
          (list 'speed (speed 1))
          (list 'acceleration (a 1)))))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot of parabolic trajectory with velocity vectors at sample points]

<!-- BUILD: run; display trajectory + vector field of velocity -->

