### Example 4.4: A Curve with Zero Torsion — Planar Curve

A curve lies in a plane if and only if its torsion is zero.

```scheme
(define (planar-curve-torsion)
  (let* ((planar (lambda (t)
                   (list (geom/cos t)
                         (geom/sin t)
                         0)))  ; z=0, planar
         (tau (curve/torsion planar))
         (t0 1))
    (list 'torsion-at-t=1 (tau t0)
          'expected 0)))
```

[VISUAL: Number line showing torsion ≈ 0]

<!-- BUILD: run; confirms planar curve has zero torsion -->

---

### Example 4.5: Non-Planar Curve — Viviani's Curve

Viviani's curve: **r(t) = (1 + cos t, sin t, 2 sin(t/2))**. It's non-planar (torsion ≠ 0).

```scheme
(define (viviani-curve-example)
  (let* ((viviani (lambda (t)
                    (list (+ 1 (geom/cos t))
                          (geom/sin t)
                          (* 2 (geom/sin (/ t 2))))))
         (tau (curve/torsion viviani))
         (kappa (curve/curvature viviani))
         (ts (math/array 0 (* 2 (const/pi)) 10)))
    (map (lambda (t)
           (list t (kappa t) (tau t)))
         ts)))
```

[VISUAL: Table of t, κ(t), τ(t) showing non-zero torsion]

<!-- BUILD: run; display as table -->

