## 6. Osculating Circle & Principal Curvatures — Surfaces in Brief

We've focused on curves, but differential geometry extends to surfaces. A surface has *two* principal curvatures at each point (the maximum and minimum curvatures of curves lying on the surface). Their product is the **Gaussian curvature**; their average is the **mean curvature**.

### Example 6.1: Osculating Circle of a Space Curve

```scheme
(define (osculating-circle-3d-example)
  (let* ((helix (lambda (t)
                  (list (geom/cos t)
                        (geom/sin t)
                        (* 0.5 t))))
         (t0 (const/pi))
         (osc (curve/osculating-circle helix t0)))
    osc))
```

[VISUAL: 3D plot of helix with osculating circle's center and radius displayed]

<!-- BUILD: run; display circle data -->

---

### Example 6.2: Surface Defined as a Graph z = f(x, y)

A surface **z = x² + y²** (a paraboloid).

```scheme
(define (surface-graph-example)
  (let* ((f (lambda (x y) (+ (* x x) (* y y))))
         (surface (curve/surface-graph f)))
    (plot/contour surface -2 2 -2 2 20)))
```

