### Example 6.7: First and Second Fundamental Forms

The **first fundamental form** encodes distances on the surface; the **second** encodes curvature.

```scheme
(define (fundamental-forms-example)
  (let* ((f (lambda (x y) (* x y)))  ; hyperbolic paraboloid
         (surface (curve/surface-graph f))
         (pt '(1 1))
         (I (curve/first-form surface pt))
         (II (curve/second-form surface pt)))
    (list 'first-form I
          'second-form II)))
```

