## 7. Geodesics & the Brachistochrone — Shortest Paths and Fastest Descents

A **geodesic** is a curve on a surface that locally minimizes distance — the \"straight line\" of that surface. On a plane, geodesics are lines; on a sphere, they're great circles.

The **brachistochrone** is the curve of fastest descent under gravity — the path a bead slides down in minimum time. It's a cycloid, found by the calculus of variations.

### Example 7.1: Geodesic Distance on a Surface

```scheme
(define (geodesic-distance-example)
  (let* ((f (lambda (x y) 0))  ; flat plane z=0
         (surface (curve/surface-graph f))
         (P '(0 0))
         (Q '(3 4))
         (d (curve/geodesic-distance surface P Q)))
    (list 'points (list P Q)
          'geodesic-distance d
          'expected (math/pow (+ 9 16) 0.5))))
```

