### Example 8.2: Euler-Lagrange Residual

The Euler-Lagrange equation governs extremal curves (geodesics, brachistochrones). The residual measures how far a curve is from satisfying it.

```scheme
(define (euler-lagrange-example)
  (let* ((L (lambda (x y yp) (math/pow (+ 1 (* yp yp)) 0.5)))  ; arc length Lagrangian
         (y (lambda (x) x))  ; test curve y=x
         (yp (lambda (x) 1))
         (ypp (lambda (x) 0))
         (x0 1)
         (residual (curve/euler-lagrange-residual L y yp ypp x0)))
    (list 'residual residual)))
```

[VISUAL: Number line showing residual (should be near zero for a geodesic)]

<!-- BUILD: run; display numeric result -->

---

### Example 8.3: Lagrangian Action

The **action** is the integral of the Lagrangian along a path. Geodesics minimize it.

```scheme
(define (lagrangian-action-example)
  (let* ((L (lambda (x y yp) (math/pow (+ 1 (* yp yp)) 0.5)))
         (y (lambda (x) x))
         (yp (lambda (x) 1))
         (action (phys/lagrangian-action L y yp 0 2)))
    (list 'action action
          'expected (* 2 (math/pow 2 0.5)))))
```

[VISUAL: Number line comparing action to expected value]

<!-- BUILD: run; display comparison -->

